Seattle's Starbucks, a brick-and-mortar retailer, proposed buying Williams-Sonoma, a brick-and-mortar retailer, as an Internet play--an opportunity for Starbucks to hitch a ride on Williams-Sonoma's e-commerce business. Starbucks declined to comment on the acquisition attempt, first reported in The Chronicle on Friday, and Williams-Sonoma will say only that it is not for sale. Starbucks will promote Kozmo and train its sales staff to answer questions about the Internet company. Starbucks will consider acquisitions and investments in other companies that provide some of the products to be sold on the Web site. ``This all speaks to what most Internet companies are facing, and that's the high cost of customer acquisition,'' said Howard Schultz, Starbucks' chairman and chief executive. ''With Joe, we want to encourage those traditions,'' Howard Schultz, chairman of Seattle-based Starbucks Coffee Co., said in a statement. 

